	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=203677><span id= >Palamus</span></a><br><span id=notbold>13 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [2.75]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Hail Brethren!<br><br>I've been playing EQ for 4 years this November and Human Paladins have been my primary characters.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>Over the years I've learned the obvious about Solo'ing:  Damage Output and Damage Avoidance are the keys to survival while soloing for the Paladin.  The obvious AC and HP's are included in Damage Avoidance and over the years I have learned to respect the statistic &quot;Agility&quot;,   that plays a key part in damage avoidance.  As you know it increases AC.  Being a player of human Paladins, whose agility is low to start with I've found myself scrounging for agility gear and sacraficing other statistics that are also essential.<br><br>However, I am quite pleased with my current gear and stats, but alas I find that I am not striking my opponent a good percentage of the time, hence, loosing agro and the ability to MT even though my ac and hp's are superior to other members of the group.  Ironically, my current Paladin's best soloing periods were when he wore Crustacean armor and now he wears Ornate.  <br><br>I have a theory that is based on a relationship/ratio between Strength, Agility, Dexsterity that would allow a player to achieve a 90% contact rate, hitting in the high range of their damage ability 70% of the time.  There have been periods I have achieved this, but in order to incease magic resistance or ac/stam/hp's I have lost that balance and I am at a loss again.<br>My stats are phenominal for my level in regards to AC and HP's and I have acquired thru the blessings of many some of the best droppable armor available to Paladins today.  Its sad that I have lost the tanking ability because I have lost the ability to deliver sufficient damage as I have done in the past.  <br><br>My best stats when contact was made on 90% of the swings was when my stats were 157 str, 108 agility and 93 dex.  Amazingly I proc'd 3 times on a 3-5 minute fight and some consider this dex very low, but I assure you I saw only an 1 extra proc with increase in dex and a drop in contact percentage.  Currently my stats are 187 str, 133 agi and 115 dex.  I've noticed that suprisingly a raise in agi allowed me to hit harder and an enormous amount of dex caused me to miss the mob very often.  With HoS and 255, str, 255 dex and 133 agility I am lucky to hit the mob 10% of the time.  This is entirely unacceptable.  I have witness changes in my damage mitigation that dispells the myths of old. ie, Dex makes you hit more often, agi makes you get hit less, strength makes you hit harder.  I honestly believe there is a ratio in effect here.  A balance between str, agi and dex exists that allows a melee to achieve its maximum damage dealing capacity.  Something that Sony/Verant did not want us to decipher and something that is used in creating NPC's ability to deal damage, as all have witness some mobs do relatively high damage and contact rates.   If you doubt this, turn your hits and misses on and NPC hits and misses on.<br><br>I realize that other factors play in here that I cannot control, ie the agility, ac and str of the mob I am fighting as each mob is different, but this comparison is made in changes on the same types of mobs as I progress in levels.<br><br>If you are 55+ and find that you hit more than 75% of your swings, plz post your stats here.  I am referring to non-buffed stats, ie no str, agi or dex buffs other than the level of yaulp you use.<br><br>Is there anyone else that has found this comparison or studied the relativity between these 3 statistics?<br><br>Thanks<br></p>&nbsp;<br>Sir Palamus Holyblade<br>60th Soldier of Mithaniel Marr<br>Commander,<br>Knights of the Holy Blade<br>E'ci</td></td></tr>
